UPDATE public.blog_posts SET
  blocks_es = '[{"id":"002e29fb-efed-40d3-8c19-6050fba9ba79","type":"paragraph","html":"Has visto el patrón una y otra vez: el cronograma dice que el proyecto termina en marzo, pero en abril siguen reasignando gente. El presupuesto se aprobó en enero y en junio descubres que llevas el doble de horas consumidas. La gestión de proyectos se queda en el tablero de tareas y nadie conecta esas tareas con quién hace qué, cuántas horas tiene cada uno y qué margen deja el proyecto."},{"id":"9ed32227-88b9-4fb7-a383-71be52761eec","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"Cuando el cronograma, el presupuesto y los recursos no van de la mano, los proyectos se retrasan, se disparan los costes o el equipo termina sobrecargado. Esta guía recorre cómo unir las tres piezas: cronograma, presupuesto por proyectos y capacidad del equipo, con ejemplos prácticos y un repaso a las herramientas que realmente ayudan."},{"id":"02820501-43cc-4663-b61d-d83506aa11ff","type":"toc"},{"id":"6a8aaa49-5e3e-4d26-851a-67f00a38d0b0","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Qué es la planificación de proyectos","anchorId":"que-es-planificacion"},{"id":"6c8df64e-93f8-4771-8106-372ca7742ff6","type":"paragraph","html":"La planificación de proyectos es la parte de la gestión de proyectos en la que defines qué hay que hacer, en qué orden, con qué recursos y en qué plazos. No es solo una lista de tareas: es decidir las fases de un proyecto, asignar responsabilidades, estimar tiempos y costes y dejar un marco claro para el seguimiento y la evaluación. La cicatriz aparece cuando nadie lo “acuerda” en serio y luego el proyecto se re-plantea en la primera crisis."},{"id":"69ea7a34-145c-470e-8ada-6428110ec278","type":"paragraph","html":"En la práctica, la planificación suele organizarse en fases. Aunque cada metodología las nombra distinto (project management clásico, Scrum, etc.), suele haber un inicio (alcance y objetivos), una fase de planificación (cronograma, presupuesto, recursos), la ejecución y el cierre. Lo que nos interesa aquí es que en la fase de planificación es donde se construye el cronograma, se fija el presupuesto del proyecto y se decide cómo se cubren los recursos para llevarlo a cabo."},{"id":"b6f677ea-807f-464a-9a1f-34d31332811c","type":"paragraph","html":"Sin esa base, el proyecto se convierte en una sucesión de urgencias: no sabes si vas bien o mal hasta que llega la facturación o el cliente reclama. Por eso tiene sentido tratar el cronograma, el presupuesto y los recursos como un mismo sistema, no como tres documentos sueltos."},{"id":"c8320387-729f-4a18-a9a3-bc0b55d84c94","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Las fases de un proyecto (resumen)"},{"id":"8f5f08c6-749b-4280-b351-9959e71c66fb","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Inicio"},{"id":"8a64f61c-f31a-4e22-aadb-c2f7c81a269d","type":"paragraph","html":"Alcance y objetivos"},{"id":"597ee9ad-d59c-46fc-91e5-4f9731cdbf75","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Planificación"},{"id":"456dba10-f86e-4d5c-a316-eaf1e6c59392","type":"paragraph","html":"Cronograma, presupuesto, recursos"},{"id":"5072369a-bcfa-4f6c-ad20-c4d27a9e544e","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Ejecución"},{"id":"3e6f6ca4-1638-4e0a-bcaa-29ee162a98e5","type":"paragraph","html":"Seguimiento y ajustes"},{"id":"43a08675-e38c-42bc-b075-ae0cd2b00ce3","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Cierre"},{"id":"8f51d873-2d79-4550-aaa5-e758fc0dc32e","type":"paragraph","html":"Evaluación y lecciones"},{"id":"286cfe97-5d94-4fec-9749-ff74dcce712b","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. El cronograma y el diagrama de Gantt","anchorId":"cronograma-gantt"},{"id":"9a6fe488-fd1c-4aca-9d1d-8976b252fcd7","type":"paragraph","html":"El cronograma de un proyecto es la línea temporal de hitos y tareas: qué se hace y cuándo. La forma más visual de representarlo es el diagrama de Gantt: barras sobre una escala de tiempo que muestran la duración de cada actividad y, en muchas herramientas, las dependencias entre ellas. Sirve para ver de un vistazo si las fechas encajan y qué tareas son críticas. La cicatriz es que el Gantt “cuadra” en pantalla… pero cuando se repiten urgencias, el mismo recurso aparece en tres frentes."},{"id":"86887f8f-a8b5-4714-91bc-58f354a6e288","type":"paragraph","html":"Un diagrama de Gantt bien usado te ayuda a responder preguntas como: ¿cuándo empieza y termina cada fase?, ¿qué tareas bloquean a otras?, ¿hay huecos o solapamientos evidentes? Herramientas como cronogramas online o software de project management suelen incluir una vista Gantt; también puedes hacer un diagrama de Gantt en Excel con una plantilla o usar una herramienta específica. Lo importante es que el cronograma sea creíble: que refleje dependencias reales y que, en la medida de lo posible, esté alineado con la capacidad de quien va a ejecutar el trabajo."},{"id":"a3c8de23-0755-4926-b130-6335d58c7192","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Cronograma solo por tareas vs. cronograma con recursos"},{"id":"0c607ad4-67d9-477a-bfeb-fe0c0173e8f9","type":"paragraph","html":"El Gantt clásico muestra plazos; no suele mostrar quién hace qué ni cuántas horas tiene cada uno."},{"id":"d0bee66b-8726-4f01-acff-18cf3d211dae","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Solo tareas y plazos"},{"id":"e5d54ad8-a2e4-40aa-89ed-fd560ae6c8fa","type":"paragraph","html":"Ves fechas y dependencias. No ves si la misma persona está en tres proyectos la misma semana."},{"id":"5ff01632-8ed5-464c-a7e6-e675ee4abf89","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Tareas + recursos y horas"},{"id":"4ab9544c-e3f9-4fda-a566-b9351ccd6ac7","type":"paragraph","html":"Cronograma alineado con capacidad: quién hace qué y con cuántas horas. Evita sobrecargas ocultas."},{"id":"7639bfb6-f34b-4775-804d-bf11fc51d6f2","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>Limitación habitual del Gantt</strong> Puedes tener un cronograma perfecto en el papel y, en la realidad, que tres proyectos pidan al mismo recurso en la misma semana. Por eso el siguiente paso lógico es conectar el cronograma con los recursos: quién hace qué y con cuántas horas."},{"id":"5af76779-f6fb-4e60-9aba-a1c681eaa8ed","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Presupuesto del proyecto","anchorId":"presupuesto-triangulo"},{"id":"a990adab-4d9e-4898-9edc-e1a0090b58a8","type":"paragraph","html":"El presupuesto de un proyecto fija cuánto vas a gastar (o cuánto vas a invertir en horas y costes) para entregar el alcance acordado. En muchas agencias y equipos de servicios, el presupuesto por proyectos se construye a partir de las horas: horas estimadas por rol o por persona, multiplicadas por un coste o por un precio de venta. Una matriz de presupuesto del proyecto puede desglosar por fases, por paquetes de trabajo o por mes, según cómo factures o controles. La cicatriz suele ser ese enero en que aprueban el “X horas”, y en el primer cambio de alcance el número deja de protegerte."},{"id":"a0a0a568-7f48-4808-85c4-453eb7157247","type":"paragraph","html":"La relación con el cronograma es directa: si el cronograma se alarga, las horas reales suelen dispararse y el presupuesto se desvía. El famoso triángulo de la gestión de proyectos (alcance, tiempo, coste) sigue vigente: si cambias uno, sueles afectar a los otros."},{"id":"893ac736-7b2c-4d25-bf23-284fca8acdda","type":"paragraph","html":"Por eso tiene sentido que el presupuesto no sea un número suelto, sino horas y costes asignados a las mismas fases y tareas que ya tienes en el cronograma. Así, cuando hagas el seguimiento, podrás comparar horas presupuestadas con horas reales y ver si el proyecto sigue dentro del margen."},{"id":"eb72be07-6834-4e43-b440-6319a2ff0b51","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"El triángulo alcance – tiempo – coste"},{"id":"be55e23b-b6dc-4570-9940-49ba5d649460","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Alcance"},{"id":"d3b14bab-4e24-4357-b89f-b37cd664b360","type":"paragraph","html":"Qué se entrega (entregables, requisitos)"},{"id":"9d2df53c-f86c-4227-8c98-8b0f1b8948ec","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Tiempo"},{"id":"af1d3c1e-b2f6-4c16-9798-13021518fa3e","type":"paragraph","html":"Plazos y cronograma"},{"id":"304fa295-06bf-4e08-8446-883dc46a422a","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Coste"},{"id":"b70cd5e4-c0e2-409c-ac17-1f9923744c11","type":"paragraph","html":"Presupuesto (horas × tarifa, otros costes)"},{"id":"0839f29e-8958-4445-aa4d-191d443398b7","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Cambiar uno suele impactar en los otros dos. Por eso el presupuesto debe ligarse a las mismas fases y tareas del cronograma.</em>"},{"id":"69fe8f9d-0fd2-46bc-8b70-9c3440d8e2c2","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Recursos y capacidad","anchorId":"recursos-capacidad"},{"id":"10f832f3-5ca5-4447-8faa-beae39e0fbc0","type":"paragraph","html":"Los recursos para llevar a cabo un proyecto son, en la mayoría de los casos, las personas: su tiempo y su capacidad. La capacidad del equipo es la cantidad de horas disponibles en un periodo (día, semana, mes) descontando vacaciones, bajas y otras ausencias. Si no tienes claro cuántas horas tiene cada persona por semana, es muy fácil asignar más trabajo del que pueden hacer o, al revés, dejar capacidad sin usar. Lo que duele es asignar “capacidad bruta” y descubrir, dos semanas después, que la capacidad neta real era bastante menos."},{"id":"83783e2c-98dc-4f37-8c2e-2c6b461618a6","type":"paragraph","html":"La asignación de horas es el puente entre el cronograma y el presupuesto: quién dedica cuántas horas a qué proyecto en cada semana. Cuando esa asignación se hace de forma explícita (por ejemplo con un planificador semanal o mensual por horas), puedes ver sobrecargas e infrautilización antes de que se conviertan en retrasos o en márgenes comidos."},{"id":"688b85b6-8db3-455d-b6f9-d2c17d228239","type":"paragraph","html":"Esta forma de trabajar está muy alineada con el timeboxing: asignar bloques de tiempo concretos a proyectos o tareas en lugar de solo listar tareas sin tiempo. La técnica la recogemos con más detalle en la guía sobre qué es el timeboxing."},{"id":"945d2d32-fbce-419f-9f5c-0ae3c507b7b5","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Sin visibilidad de capacidad"},{"id":"4bbd0f75-3646-47b5-8631-e60ec9448b27","type":"paragraph","html":"Asignas tareas sin saber cuántas horas tiene cada persona. Resultado: sobrecarga, retrasos y márgenes que se comen sin que nadie lo vea a tiempo."},{"id":"781602f3-d9ce-456e-9f73-5c3aff5e4974","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Planificación por horas"},{"id":"b053c280-a3e5-4803-ba89-cdc5808f371c","type":"paragraph","html":"Ves quién tiene cuántas horas libres y cuántas asignadas por proyecto. Detectas sobrecargas antes de que ocurran y ajustas el cronograma o el alcance."},{"id":"210e5927-1834-413d-9a1a-70f62eea3eb9","type":"paragraph","html":"qué es el timeboxing"},{"id":"5071bc57-28eb-4845-9d6a-c36013f26621","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>En resumen: el cronograma te dice cuándo; el presupuesto, cuánto; los recursos y la capacidad, quién y con cuántas horas. Unir los tres evita que los proyectos vivan solo en el tablero de tareas y que la rentabilidad se descubra cuando ya es tarde.</strong>"},{"id":"f4b9a6ca-dd5d-4815-885b-d95570bfa5bd","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>💡 Cápsula Taimbox: Cronograma y capacidad en un solo sitio</strong> En Taimbox el planificador muestra semana a semana quién hace qué y con cuántas horas. Así unes cronograma, presupuesto por proyectos y recursos sin tener que cruzar tres herramientas."},{"id":"f9cdcb71-b078-4b11-9fe0-ea0abd491fe5","type":"cta","text":"Ver planificador de recursos","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"a83365df-55f6-4349-8dd5-e277bcdf9576","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Seguimiento, KPIs y dashboard de proyectos","anchorId":"seguimiento-kpis"},{"id":"d05c3560-1495-430a-8797-f7c474316c96","type":"paragraph","html":"El seguimiento y la evaluación de proyectos consisten en comparar lo planificado con lo real: avance, horas consumidas, costes y, si aplica, satisfacción del cliente. Para eso sirven los indicadores: el KPI de un proyecto puede ser el avance frente al plan, las horas reales frente a las presupuestadas o el margen actual del proyecto. La cicatriz es cuando el dashboard “te da la razón” tarde: el cliente ya se enfadó y ya consumiste el buffer."},{"id":"9893eb3c-8152-4505-99c2-e753685ac023","type":"paragraph","html":"Un dashboard de proyectos que merezca la pena suele mostrar al menos: estado de cada proyecto (en plazo, en riesgo, retrasado), horas asignadas vs. horas reales (o vs. presupuesto) y carga por persona o por equipo. Así ves si un proyecto se está comiendo más horas de las previstas y si alguien está sobreasignado."},{"id":"b3d70eae-2722-4853-af16-9fe9c8e9cdc5","type":"paragraph","html":"En una agencia pequeña o mediana, tener un único lugar donde cruzar cronograma, presupuesto y horas reales suele marcar la diferencia entre reaccionar a tiempo y enterarte cuando el cliente ya está enfadado."},{"id":"e94b5ec1-edb6-4cc4-b278-c8cb999ea17b","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Avance vs. plan"},{"id":"89572164-fbd3-49c5-a039-4e52e6c3c6cd","type":"paragraph","html":"¿Vamos por donde tocaba? Porcentaje de tareas o hitos completados respecto al cronograma."},{"id":"3e83eb42-b125-4581-9eda-9645185a4fcb","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Horas reales vs. presupuestadas"},{"id":"ee97f703-b59d-4046-9700-82968bd58d3b","type":"paragraph","html":"¿Nos estamos pasando de horas? Si las reales superan las previstas, el margen cae."},{"id":"792639ca-7a0f-4346-b2ba-42d31e00dcd0","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Margen del proyecto"},{"id":"acf8e824-bffe-42bb-b4c2-b58b2adf49f3","type":"paragraph","html":"Ingresos menos costes (horas × tarifa, etc.). El indicador que conecta tiempo y rentabilidad."},{"id":"a8a49393-8811-413a-a681-d8a86816b901","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. Herramientas de gestión de proyectos","anchorId":"herramientas"},{"id":"06be51c5-55e3-4ece-b87c-b8865d96e65c","type":"paragraph","html":"Las herramientas de gestión de proyectos cubren necesidades distintas. Los tableros tipo Kanban (Trello, Asana, ClickUp, Notion para proyectos) son muy útiles para el estado de las tareas y el flujo de trabajo; muchos incluyen también vista de cronograma o diagrama de Gantt. La cicatriz es tener “tres verdades”: una para tareas, otra para horas y otra para margen, y terminar decidiendo a dedo en cada crisis."},{"id":"0eee49c9-e99a-4fe2-b204-6b390b78e108","type":"paragraph","html":"Para conectar tiempo, capacidad y rentabilidad hacen falta herramientas que trabajen con horas de forma explícita. En Taimbox nos centramos en ese tramo: planificación de recursos por horas, cronograma de quién hace qué cada semana, y reportes de rentabilidad por proyecto y por cliente."},{"id":"e5a3dd5d-6054-4203-be8b-0c00566af23c","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"¿Qué resuelve cada tipo de herramienta?"},{"id":"8135ce32-65d7-4f17-959f-ec18d8ebf90e","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Tableros y Gantt"},{"id":"44bb25ca-5182-4135-99b1-0bdd7a3c6287","type":"paragraph","html":"Estado de tareas, flujo de trabajo, dependencias y plazos. No suelen mostrar capacidad ni horas por persona ni margen por proyecto."},{"id":"e0ba0611-7aac-4e78-8c2e-ad0a4a56e8cf","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Planificación por horas y recursos"},{"id":"e58c523a-1b03-46f0-b79f-1bb37ec60d4d","type":"paragraph","html":"Quién hace qué y con cuántas horas. Presupuesto por proyectos ligado a esas horas y reportes de margen (asignado vs. real)."},{"id":"81f32c69-a54d-4e37-bcda-fde72795655d","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>📊 Cápsula Taimbox: Planificador + reportes de rentabilidad</strong> Planifica por horas en el planificador, sigue el avance en el dashboard y revisa margen por proyecto y por cliente en los reportes de rentabilidad. Todo en una sola plataforma."},{"id":"a08d01c3-f5c8-4a2e-bfa2-ad47239fd3d5","type":"cta","text":"Planificador","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"ccdad832-f441-4acf-aeb6-99e1c4018e64","type":"cta","text":"Reportes de rentabilidad","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"234ca780-2dc9-4485-b949-528dc015eabf","type":"paragraph","html":"Tarifas y planes concretos en la página de precios"},{"id":"2cda4f6b-1b6b-42e6-b5b9-4a7940795be9","type":"paragraph","html":"Planificar un proyecto de forma sólida implica alinear cronograma, presupuesto y recursos: qué se hace y cuándo, cuánto cuesta y quién lo hace con cuántas horas. El diagrama de Gantt y el cronograma son la base visual; el presupuesto por proyectos y la asignación de horas son lo que evita que todo se quede en intenciones. El seguimiento con KPIs y un dashboard sencillo te permite corregir antes de que el proyecto se desvíe del todo."},{"id":"8debff47-84ba-459b-997d-0abbba9ca91a","type":"paragraph","html":"Si en tu agencia o equipo ya usáis tableros de tareas pero os falta ese enlace entre tiempo, capacidad y rentabilidad, probar un planificador por horas puede ser el siguiente paso."},{"id":"546be8e2-1e90-48af-8b0e-38e1cd9ed425","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Preguntas frecuentes sobre planificación de proyectos","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"c0bc66ca-d4a8-4eef-9d9e-f216bee01822","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"¿El diagrama de Gantt es suficiente para gestionar un proyecto?","a":"Para plazos y dependencias sí. Para saber si vas a cumplir el presupuesto y si tu equipo tiene capacidad real, no: necesitas cruzar el cronograma con las horas por persona y con el presupuesto por proyecto."},{"q":"¿Qué KPI de proyecto tiene más sentido en una agencia?","a":"Horas reales vs. presupuestadas y margen por proyecto (o por cliente). Son los que conectan el tiempo con la rentabilidad. El avance frente al cronograma ayuda, pero sin horas y margen no ves si el proyecto es rentable."},{"q":"¿Puedo usar un tablero Kanban y un planificador por horas a la vez?","a":"Sí. Muchos equipos usan Trello, Asana o similar para el día a día de las tareas y una herramienta de planificación por horas (como Taimbox) para capacidad, presupuesto y margen. Se complementan: el tablero para el flujo, el planificador para el tiempo y el dinero."}]},{"id":"8d8b13ca-ac1a-40ca-81ac-7dacf85b2406","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Planifica por horas y recupera el control del margen","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"c5534024-aca5-4541-b49f-d0cd9fec61d7","type":"paragraph","html":"Cronograma, presupuesto y recursos en un solo lugar; Taimbox se puede explorar sin compromiso."},{"id":"c45654fb-387f-4677-b0be-ee8022a985e1","type":"cta","text":"Ver planificador de recursos","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"21da14df-58c7-4019-af83-574e80002b15","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Escrito por el equipo de Taimbox — Gestión de recursos y rentabilidad para agencias.</em>"},{"id":"82d0e6e2-7024-481c-bbd3-15ddfb614ed5","type":"relatedPost","slug":"que-es-timeboxing"}]'::jsonb,
  blocks_en = '[{"id":"e21045ab-b909-48ee-80c6-2b0a24929b25","type":"paragraph","html":"You have seen the pattern again and again: the schedule says the project ends in March, but in April people are still being reassigned. The budget was approved in January and by June you discover you have burned twice the planned hours. Project management stays in the task board and nobody connects those tasks with who does what, how many hours each person has, and what margin the project leaves."},{"id":"5473b709-23f5-4eb0-b888-af11ff1abcb0","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"When schedule, budget, and resources are not aligned, projects get delayed, costs explode, or the team ends up overloaded. This guide walks through how to connect the three pieces: schedule, project budgets, and team capacity, with practical examples and a review of the tools that actually help."},{"id":"9145f0b6-6276-4739-bbf9-41cadaa7fe8a","type":"toc"},{"id":"2f1cdc3b-5040-46ed-8ea5-73f47f33e034","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. What is project planning","anchorId":"que-es-planificacion"},{"id":"dbe90e02-d859-464f-8109-2e5c311b1acf","type":"paragraph","html":"Project planning is the part of project management where you define what needs to be done, in what order, with which resources, and within what timeframes. It is not just a task list: it is deciding the phases of a project, assigning responsibilities, estimating time and costs, and setting a clear framework for monitoring and evaluation. The scar appears when nobody really “agrees” on it and the project is redefined at the first crisis."},{"id":"2c80ff42-e7ee-4454-b54d-132f3eb01a87","type":"paragraph","html":"In practice, planning is usually organized into phases. Although each methodology names them differently (classic project management, Scrum, etc.), there is usually a start (scope and objectives), a planning phase (schedule, budget, resources), execution, and closure. What matters here is that in the planning phase you build the schedule, set the project budget, and decide how resources will cover the work."},{"id":"645785f4-417f-4a76-a2bc-52399b058788","type":"paragraph","html":"Without that foundation, the project becomes a chain of emergencies: you do not know whether you are on track until invoicing arrives or the client complains. That is why it makes sense to treat schedule, budget, and resources as a single system, not as three separate documents."},{"id":"4574b07e-b028-48d0-b2d4-ec027270aed7","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"The phases of a project (summary)"},{"id":"533a7d25-b541-437c-8d5b-e12f0241f1f4","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Start"},{"id":"df476040-bc95-4939-be04-6f0976f9a4b6","type":"paragraph","html":"Scope and objectives"},{"id":"3def543e-ef85-4bef-b2ca-317a1c4ce129","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Planning"},{"id":"78274fca-34fd-4ce6-a8bc-840d53e2e282","type":"paragraph","html":"Schedule, budget, resources"},{"id":"ab92c553-f21c-4a32-a28c-35b511b3a3ba","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Execution"},{"id":"28693368-1d5f-4b60-8679-29126b554030","type":"paragraph","html":"Monitoring and adjustments"},{"id":"fcc857c0-60c6-40dd-acc5-428f941a86f0","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Closure"},{"id":"d8d1c36c-a351-4f05-a341-49db99f9031f","type":"paragraph","html":"Evaluation and lessons learned"},{"id":"6cc7c533-595e-4d74-a42e-800abca2da50","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. The schedule and the Gantt chart","anchorId":"cronograma-gantt"},{"id":"a034ae64-095c-4929-8423-a4b751f7d2fa","type":"paragraph","html":"A project schedule is the timeline of milestones and tasks: what is done and when. The most visual way to represent it is the Gantt chart: bars over a time scale that show the duration of each activity and, in many tools, the dependencies between them. It lets you see at a glance whether dates fit together and which tasks are critical. The scar is that the Gantt “fits” on screen… but when emergencies repeat, the same resource appears in three places at once."},{"id":"10c7ddd6-3f19-4e2d-a64e-dc5b6256fffd","type":"paragraph","html":"A well‑used Gantt chart helps you answer questions such as: when does each phase start and end? Which tasks block others? Are there obvious gaps or overlaps? Tools like online timelines or project‑management software usually include a Gantt view; you can also build a Gantt chart in Excel with a template or use a dedicated tool. The key is that the schedule is credible: it reflects real dependencies and, as far as possible, is aligned with the capacity of the people who will do the work."},{"id":"4d745d5d-dabb-4be2-a894-09dd6ea40bb1","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Task‑only schedule vs. schedule with resources"},{"id":"5900eaa0-e86f-4d9a-9971-f7bf6f81b250","type":"paragraph","html":"A classic Gantt shows deadlines; it usually does not show who does what or how many hours each person has."},{"id":"adfa83ef-c788-48c1-8082-44595a12e712","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Only tasks and deadlines"},{"id":"24db316a-70a8-4a8d-868e-cd2634fe633b","type":"paragraph","html":"You see dates and dependencies. You do not see whether the same person is on three projects in the same week."},{"id":"14b51b3d-9974-4c92-b3da-1ff2d525cc52","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Tasks + resources and hours"},{"id":"1e6c9576-dfeb-4e55-b445-b860ac0f8f0f","type":"paragraph","html":"A schedule aligned with capacity: who does what and with how many hours. It prevents hidden overloads."},{"id":"d42b76c8-abe5-41cc-bef0-81a951e97c7f","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>A common limitation of Gantt charts</strong> You can have a perfect schedule on paper and, in reality, three projects all asking for the same resource in the same week. That is why the logical next step is to connect the schedule with resources: who does what and with how many hours."},{"id":"c770186b-1156-4ce7-b865-aa522159e101","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Project budget","anchorId":"presupuesto-triangulo"},{"id":"2f8360bb-5a40-49a5-9e09-98841e3fcba9","type":"paragraph","html":"A project budget sets how much you are going to spend (or invest in hours and costs) to deliver the agreed scope. In many agencies and service teams, project budgets are built from hours: estimated hours by role or person, multiplied by a cost or selling rate. A project budget matrix can be broken down by phase, by work package, or by month, depending on how you bill or track performance. The scar is often that January when “X hours” are approved, and at the first scope change that number stops protecting you."},{"id":"b0f0d1de-9532-49e3-8b0f-53b353f81a94","type":"paragraph","html":"The relationship with the schedule is direct: if the schedule lengthens, actual hours tend to spike and the budget drifts. The classic project‑management triangle (scope, time, cost) is still alive: change one, and you typically affect the others."},{"id":"fd25d855-1d38-48a9-9828-6e6922ff50c0","type":"paragraph","html":"That is why it makes sense for the budget not to be a standalone number, but hours and costs assigned to the same phases and tasks you already have in the schedule. Then, when you do tracking, you can compare budgeted hours with actual hours and see whether the project is still within margin."},{"id":"357556b4-5749-48f4-84af-96d316a2a8bf","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"The scope–time–cost triangle"},{"id":"c73c37df-59ee-4ce4-9d63-08795e091018","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Scope"},{"id":"233e39fb-0844-48bf-af92-20d235e4b970","type":"paragraph","html":"What is delivered (deliverables, requirements)"},{"id":"d7e85929-04ef-4730-8432-138196e3f381","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Time"},{"id":"c918a49a-1fc6-47b6-b8b3-041d385d5def","type":"paragraph","html":"Deadlines and schedule"},{"id":"7872fd18-d9e0-4a82-950c-d10b375e51f9","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Cost"},{"id":"6bbf3051-c754-4700-a47d-a033cc31de15","type":"paragraph","html":"Budget (hours × rate, other costs)"},{"id":"4294273c-70a8-4117-a3cc-b602d602ddea","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Changing one usually impacts the other two. That is why the budget should be tied to the same phases and tasks as the schedule.</em>"},{"id":"8cdd8fd4-731b-4a16-ac17-714210040e01","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Resources and capacity","anchorId":"recursos-capacidad"},{"id":"4de3b2a6-d093-403f-bacc-ba4c711950f9","type":"paragraph","html":"The resources to deliver a project are, in most cases, people: their time and their capacity. Team capacity is the number of hours available in a period (day, week, month) after subtracting holidays, sick leave, and other absences. If you are not clear on how many hours each person has per week, it is very easy to assign more work than they can do or, conversely, leave capacity unused. What hurts is planning with “gross capacity” and discovering two weeks later that the real net capacity was much lower."},{"id":"e9293ded-1268-4df3-82c6-c58e1f3e2269","type":"paragraph","html":"Hour allocation is the bridge between schedule and budget: who spends how many hours on which project each week. When that allocation is made explicitly (for example with a weekly or monthly hour‑based planner), you can see overloads and under‑utilization before they become delays or eaten‑up margins."},{"id":"a3b71890-a641-44db-a889-f7d4303bb68a","type":"paragraph","html":"This way of working is very close to timeboxing: assigning specific time blocks to projects or tasks instead of just listing tasks without time. We go deeper into the technique in the guide on what timeboxing is."},{"id":"af1ff0d9-11a2-49be-90b6-69efca205ab0","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"No visibility on capacity"},{"id":"e5522c88-e068-4653-b2df-7412701a4090","type":"paragraph","html":"You assign tasks without knowing how many hours each person has. The result: overload, delays, and margins disappearing with nobody noticing in time."},{"id":"d515d01a-9d1e-4c48-a621-869af456f2f0","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hour‑based planning"},{"id":"0fac476a-2ee1-4032-9e2f-9fc3076dc25d","type":"paragraph","html":"You see who has how many free hours and how many assigned hours per project. You spot overloads before they happen and adjust schedule or scope."},{"id":"b129334a-7b5d-4f79-a93c-448bb2ea35b0","type":"paragraph","html":"what timeboxing is"},{"id":"c35db4d7-89a1-4287-b88d-2e4f7a59facd","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>In short: the schedule tells you when; the budget, how much; resources and capacity, who and with how many hours. Connecting all three prevents projects from living only in the task board and profitability being discovered when it is already too late.</strong>"},{"id":"f7211a72-46eb-4b7e-a26f-e3fc4b91ce7e","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>💡 Taimbox capsule: Schedule and capacity in one place</strong> In Taimbox, the planner shows week by week who does what and with how many hours. That way you connect schedule, project budgets, and resources without having to juggle three tools."},{"id":"26b967a4-4284-45e0-861a-0435df02d302","type":"cta","text":"See the resource planner","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"a14fb5de-ac9d-4712-a408-21769ebdd314","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Monitoring, KPIs, and project dashboard","anchorId":"seguimiento-kpis"},{"id":"f613c29c-00c6-43cd-9eb2-93fc21306895","type":"paragraph","html":"Monitoring and evaluating projects means comparing plan and reality: progress, hours burned, costs, and, where relevant, client satisfaction. This is what indicators are for: a project KPI might be progress versus plan, actual hours versus budgeted hours, or the project’s current margin. The scar is when the dashboard “proves you right” too late: the client is already upset and you have already burned through the buffer."},{"id":"d1aadd8b-359b-4fe9-8582-8f031eeadc15","type":"paragraph","html":"A worthwhile project dashboard usually shows at least: the status of each project (on track, at risk, delayed), assigned hours vs. actual hours (or vs. budget), and workload per person or team. That way you see whether a project is eating more hours than planned and whether someone is over‑assigned."},{"id":"570e56bc-b806-4ef1-906e-7db49aef0265","type":"paragraph","html":"In a small or mid‑sized agency, having a single place where you can cross schedule, budget, and actual hours often makes the difference between reacting in time and finding out only once the client is already upset."},{"id":"638a950a-0331-4151-9d4f-deb30826c2f3","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Progress vs. plan"},{"id":"cefb6e57-9c84-4312-8dda-213b5f609322","type":"paragraph","html":"Are we where we should be? Percentage of tasks or milestones completed versus the schedule."},{"id":"12c77792-65a6-4b10-bee6-70bc2ce83ca2","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Actual vs. budgeted hours"},{"id":"32d54c02-8d0d-4205-9310-e16c92aa45e7","type":"paragraph","html":"Are we overshooting hours? If actual hours exceed planned hours, margin falls."},{"id":"f14372ca-7008-4da1-99fe-1efcdce23596","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Project margin"},{"id":"bcd55833-3dca-462c-b8d2-5358c1db78b1","type":"paragraph","html":"Revenue minus costs (hours × rate, etc.). The indicator that connects time and profitability."},{"id":"62a76029-d9e2-4305-9291-30482cdd5f07","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. Project‑management tools","anchorId":"herramientas"},{"id":"16e7f0c9-38d9-4954-acd0-1696642efd24","type":"paragraph","html":"Project‑management tools solve different needs. Kanban‑style boards (Trello, Asana, ClickUp, Notion for projects) are very useful for task status and workflow; many also include a schedule or Gantt‑chart view. The scar is having “three truths”: one for tasks, one for hours, and one for margin, and ending up deciding by gut feel in every crisis."},{"id":"c4e6c34d-7b31-45cf-940f-f159014b2d7d","type":"paragraph","html":"To connect time, capacity, and profitability you need tools that work explicitly with hours. In Taimbox we focus on that layer: hour‑based resource planning, a schedule of who does what each week, and profitability reports by project and client."},{"id":"5af86449-0e52-4599-86b3-87bdb324cf09","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"What does each type of tool solve?"},{"id":"715d3990-ec39-4790-b436-e75eff83aabd","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Boards and Gantt charts"},{"id":"eb66d00e-3444-4d86-95cb-5777d9e388d8","type":"paragraph","html":"Task status, workflow, dependencies, and deadlines. They usually do not show capacity or hours per person or margin by project."},{"id":"8842d655-899f-411a-9560-b6799b662813","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Hour‑ and resource‑based planning"},{"id":"b35ed2cd-9c13-4d5d-801c-5b75de848bbb","type":"paragraph","html":"Who does what and with how many hours. Project budgets tied to those hours and margin reports (planned vs. actual)."},{"id":"b2ddd8c4-3e45-41f7-af52-636d7f75b51a","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>📊 Taimbox capsule: Planner + profitability reports</strong> Plan by hours in the planner, track progress in the dashboard, and review margin by project and client in the profitability reports. All in a single platform."},{"id":"11472910-af98-4a41-9beb-0ba75ca5a709","type":"cta","text":"Planner","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"177e67d2-d6f7-4629-a49d-c25d862e0242","type":"cta","text":"Profitability reports","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"1bf2bfb1-90e6-4524-b79b-98bbd38701d8","type":"paragraph","html":"Details on plans and pricing are on the pricing page"},{"id":"a74f8813-ecad-4141-bb37-9c56e4077dbc","type":"paragraph","html":"Solid project planning means aligning schedule, budget, and resources: what is done and when, how much it costs, and who does it with how many hours. The Gantt chart and schedule are the visual foundation; project budgets and hour allocation are what keep things from remaining only intentions. Tracking with KPIs and a simple dashboard lets you correct course before the project goes completely off the rails."},{"id":"f56da388-87f9-4c26-82e8-6148e46f1dca","type":"paragraph","html":"If your agency or team already uses task boards but you are missing that link between time, capacity, and profitability, trying an hour‑based planner may be the logical next step."},{"id":"a68b014d-6776-4351-ab9e-63b543d3b92d","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Frequently asked questions about project planning","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"c8f3a343-1fb5-4cfa-91c7-6dd455c513dc","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"Is a Gantt chart enough to manage a project?","a":"For deadlines and dependencies, yes. To know whether you will hit the budget and whether your team has real capacity, no: you need to cross the schedule with hours per person and the project budget."},{"q":"Which project KPI makes the most sense in an agency?","a":"Actual vs. budgeted hours and margin by project (or by client). These are the ones that connect time and profitability. Progress versus schedule helps, but without hours and margin you cannot see whether the project is profitable."},{"q":"Can I use a Kanban board and an hour‑based planner at the same time?","a":"Yes. Many teams use Trello, Asana, or similar for day‑to‑day task management and an hour‑based planning tool (such as Taimbox) for capacity, budget, and margin. They complement each other: the board for workflow, the planner for time and money."}]},{"id":"7b0eafac-8192-490f-948c-41a81c3d7e88","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Plan by hours and regain control of margin","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"90bf43ab-4b26-4f35-a56e-ab8dde09bd29","type":"paragraph","html":"Schedule, budget, and resources in one place; you can explore Taimbox with no commitment."},{"id":"0d04d39e-a63c-43dc-9fd6-2c0e6ff50917","type":"cta","text":"See the resource planner","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"dd8f5991-65d3-401f-aea4-fe74d819dc5a","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Written by the Taimbox team — Resource management and profitability for agencies.</em>"},{"id":"398dadaa-d83b-4574-96fd-2739febd550b","type":"relatedPost","slug":"que-es-timeboxing"}]'::jsonb,
  json_ld_es = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Planificación de proyectos: cronograma, presupuesto y recursos (guía práctica)","description":"Guía práctica para unir cronograma, presupuesto y capacidad del equipo. Incluye diagrama de Gantt, fases del proyecto, KPIs y herramientas de gestión de proyectos.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-18","inLanguage":"es","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/blog/planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}}]}'::jsonb,
  json_ld_en = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Project Planning: Schedule, Budget, and Resources (Practical Guide)","description":"Practical guide to combine schedule, budget, and team capacity. Includes Gantt charts, project phases, KPIs, and PM tools.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-18","inLanguage":"en","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/en/blog/project-planning-schedule-resources"}}]}'::jsonb
